'''Isador Henry Coriat''' (December 10, 1875, [[Philadelphia]] – May 26, 1943, [[Boston]]) was an American psychiatrist and neurologist. He was one of the first American psychoanalysts.<ref>Nathan G Hale: ''Freud and the Americans: The Beginnings of Psychoanalysis in the United States, 1876-1917 (Freud in America)'', Publisher: Oxford University Press,First Edition (1971), ISBN 0-19-501427-8</ref>
.

He was born in Philadelphia in 1875 as the son of Hyram Coriat and Clara née Einstein.<ref>Dictionary of American Biography volume 12. Scribner, 1959 page 190</ref> He was of Moroccan-Spanish descent on father's side and German on mother's side. He grew up in [[Boston]] and attended [[Tufts University School of Medicine|Tufts Medical School]], graduating in 1900.<ref>Andrew R. Heinze: Jews and the American Soul: Human Nature in the Twentieth Century. Princeton University Press, 2004 ISBN 0-691-11755-1 page 120-123</ref> 

He was one of the founders of [[Boston Psychoanalytic Society]], the first secretary in 1914 and president in years 1930-32. Coriat was the only Freudian analyst in Boston during the period after [[James Jackson Putnam]]'s death.<ref>International Dictionary of Psychoanalysis. Alain de Mijolla (ed.) page 207 ISBN 0-02-865994-5</ref>

Coriat worked with the Rev. [[Elwood Worcester]], served as the medical expert for the [[Emmanuel Movement]] and co-authored ''Religion and Medicine; The Moral Control of Nervous Disorders''.

Coriat married Etta Dann in 1910. He died on May 26, 1943, after a brief illness.

